<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 10:20<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I295dd720630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Documentary and Demonstrative Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7212884682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:20.</label.designator><headtext>Other writings for comparison</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The jury or testifying experts may compare other writings which have been authenticated. <eos/><bos/>Such specimens shall be furnished to the opposite party no later than 10 days prior to trial.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic62c93c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>For example, a will, not otherwise relevant to the issues at trial, could be received in evidence as demonstrative so that the <page no="372"/>signature could be used for comparison.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic62c93c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] The methods for authenticating a handwritten document include the testimony of a witness with knowledge that a matter is what it is claimed to be, non-expert opinion as to the genuineness of handwriting based upon familiarity not acquired for purposes of the litigation, and comparisons by the trier of fact or by expert witnesses with specimens that have been authenticated. <eos/><bos/>It is proper to admit portions of a letter that were authenticated as an exemplar for comparison for the trier of fact for portions that the author did not purport to have written.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic62c93c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic62c93c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017218" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-901" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I5aa655007fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-901</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A signature on a bond form was properly admitted for comparison in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017218" w-serial-number="1980115335" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5aa6a3227fc011ea988285db8533e975">Huskins v. State, 245 Ga. 541, 266 S.E.2d 163 (1980)</cite.query> (citing former O.C.G.A. § 24-7-7).<eos/><page no="372"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic62c93c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017218" w-serial-number="1957121770" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5aa718527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Byrd v. Riggs, 213 Ga. 593, 100 S.E.2d 453 (1957)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic62c93c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017218" w-serial-number="2045861837" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I5aa78d827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Cruz v. State, 347 Ga. App. 810, 821 S.E.2d 44 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 10:20<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
